blobs.content: Introducing NativeWind: A Universal Styling System

NativeWind harnesses the power of Tailwind CSS to offer a seamless styling experience across all React Native platforms. With a mission to enhance developer UX, component performance, and code maintainability, NativeWind bridges the gap between web-based and native StyleSheet implementations.
The NativeWind Advantage
By processing styles during application build and leveraging a minimal runtime, NativeWind readily applies responsive designs based on device properties like orientation and color schemes.

The Rocky Relationship with Plex

I've been a loyal Plex user since I discovered that Air Video didn't have an Android client. Although it has been mostly great for organizing and streaming my media library to my devices, I increasingly feel like Plex has lost its way by focusing on games, live TV, and movie rental services.
Exploring the Big Competitor: Jellyfin

The positive community feedback and internal praises for Jellyfin, a free and open-source media management tool, prompted me to finally check it out. Open-source projects often have great ideas and functionality, a dedicated fan base, but they also come with certain quirks.
Diving into Jellyfin
Now, I'm going swimming with the jellies to see what I've been missing out on and to evaluate the platform. This change can also involve our sponsor Zoho Desk, a context-aware help desk solution.
Plex's Dominance in Device Compatibility

One of the best things about Plex is its universal device compatibility, whether it's a Samsung Tizen TV, PlayStation 5 VR headset, or even a Facebook Portal. The first-party app seamlessly streams DVD and Blu-ray rips to numerous devices.

content: Samsung Tizen TV
PlayStation 5 VR headset
Facebook Portal

blobs.content: As a for-profit company, Plex has the financial resources to pay teams for porting their apps, testing them, and handling certification and listing procedures. As a result, Plex offers various self-hosted streaming apps, unlike many alternatives available in countries like Canada.
Official Apps and Limitations

Jellyfin has impressive official apps but many are simple web browser wrappers which sometimes have limitations. On iOS, Jellyfin Mobile (browser-based) and SwiftFin (a native app) are officially available. However, SwiftFin, while at an early stage with limited features, has advantages such as working on Apple TV.
Setting Up Plex and Jellyfin Servers

content: On a Windows desktop: As easy as running an app and following instructions
On Docker: Slightly trickier, but doable; choose between the Linux server image and the official image
On FreeBSD: Plex supports FreeBSD, Jellyfin doesn't; potential bummer for TruenNAS core (free NAS software) users

blobs.content: Setting Up Library

content: Setting up the library on either was seamless, with only minor hiccups for a few titles on Plex
Applying metadata: Slightly easier on Plex, obtaining recommendations for unrecognized titles; Jellyfin requires MovieDB
On subtitles: Automatic for both platforms, plus for accessibility
On DVD Specials and Extras: Differences in automated handling, potential user adjustments needed

blobs.content: Metadata & Home Release Extras

Both systems require placing files in specially named folders and manually entering metadata. This is an area for improvement, as there isn't a good resource for cataloging home release extras, considering their vast quantity and variations across regions.
Content Filtering

content: Jellyfin's filtering works well on web and Android, with an easy-to-follow UI and functional multiple options.
Google TV and Swiftfin have limited sorting options and don't allow multiple filters or selections.
Plex's content filtering is more robust but lacks the ability to mix and match options.

blobs.content: User Interface & Navigation

Navigating Jellyfin's default view is easier, as it shows different library types, media to continue watching, and latest additions to libraries right from the start. Plex, on the other hand, requires navigating multiple menus to filter through shows and movies.
Parental Controls

content: Jellyfin offers complete parental controls, where libraries can be restricted by account and maximum ratings can be set with accurate translation across systems.
Plex provides managed accounts with fixed restriction profiles, but customization is not possible, limiting user control.

blobs.content: Sharing & (Potential Legal Issues)

Plex allows sharing entire libraries with friends and family, much like a private Netflix. However, to access all features, invitees will need a Plex Pass of their own. Jellyfin only provides account customization option without mentioning sharing features.

THE MAPPING MEDICARE DISPARITIES TOOL QUICK START GUIDE

Chronic diseases like diabetes and cardiovascular disease significantly affect the United States and disproportionately impact racial and ethnic minorities. The Mapping Medicare Disparities (MMD) Tool contains two components: the Population View and the Hospital View. The Population View presents differences in health outcomes, utilization, and spending among subgroups. The Hospital View showcases disparities in selected health outcome and quality measures between hospitals. Visualizing the geographic differences is crucial for understanding health disparity, informing policy decisions, and targeting populations and areas for effective interventions.
How do I zoom and navigate in the map?

content: 1. Click on a county/state/territory of interest.
2. Use the mouse scroll wheel or gesture controls to zoom in/out.
3. Navigate the map by left-clicking and holding while moving your mouse or finger on your Trackpad.

blobs.content: How can I compare differences in measures in the Population View?

In the Analysis drop-down menu, selecting an option other than Base Measure allows visualization of differences between patient characteristics, comparing health outcomes, spending, or utilization. For instance, to compare the difference in diabetes prevalence rates at a county level between Asians and Whites:

content: 1. Select Prevalence under Measure.
2. Choose Within County Difference under Analysis.
3. Select Primary chronic conditions under Domain.
4. Choose Diabetes under Condition/Service.
5. Pick Asian/Pacific Islander under Race and Ethnicity.
6. Opt for White under Comparison Race and Ethnicity.

blobs.content: CMS OMH Mapping Medicare Disparities Tool Quick Start Guide
Interpreting Comparison Results in Population View

In Population View, three values (A, B, and C) are displayed when hovering over a specific county/state. Rate A is for the Primary patient group, rate B for the Comparison patient group, and rate C is the difference between A and B. A positive value indicates the Primary patient group has a higher rate, while a negative value indicates the Comparison patient group has a lower rate.
Evaluating Hospital Performance in Hospital View

In the Hospital View, users can select multiple comparisons to assess hospital performance. Comparison options include Geographic (Nation, State or County), Hospital Type (Acute Care, Children, Critical Access) or Hospital size (under 100 beds, 100 to 200 beds, over 200 beds).
Finding Additional Information
For further assistance, consult the technical documentation or frequently asked questions (FAQs) using the provided links:
